If you define a compatible SAM type, you could simply assign the method reference:

```
interface VoidIntFunc {
  void call(int i);
}

class MyClass {
    public void function(int i) {
        System.out.println(&quot;Hello, world!&quot;);
    }

    public static void main(final String... args) {
        final VoidIntFunc func = new MyClass()::function;
        func.call(42);
    }
}
```

Fortunately, Java already defines exactly this SAM type: [`java.util.function.IntConsumer`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/function/IntConsumer.html):

```
class MyClass {
    public void function(int i) {
        System.out.println(&quot;Hello, world!&quot;);
    }

    public static void main(final String... args) {
        final IntConsumer func = new MyClass()::function;
        func.accept(42);
    }
}
```

If you want an &quot;unbound&quot; method reference, get the reference of the method from the class and make sure to define the method in your SAM type with the first parameter having the type of the class/instance (this parameter will be the `this` when the method reference is called). Thanks to [user16320675](https://stackoverflow.com/users/16320675/user16320675) for pointing this out in the comments!

```
class MyClass {
    public void function(int i) {
        System.out.println(&quot;Hello, world!&quot;);
    }

    public static void main(final String... args) {
        final ToIntFunction func = MyClass::function;
        func.applyAsInt(new MyClass(), 42);
    }
}
```

*****

Other options include using Reflection to obtain a `java.lang.reflect.Method` object and invoke it or to look up a `java.lang.invoke.MethodHandle`.

Example invoking a `Method` instance:

```
class MyClass {
    public void function(int i) {
        System.out.println(&quot;Hello, world!&quot;);
    }

    public static void main(final String... args) throws Exception {
        final Method method = MyClass.class.getMethod(&quot;function&quot;, int.class);

        final MyClass obj = new MyClass();
        method.invoke(obj, 42);
    }
}
```

The example for method handles is similar, but requires a slightly different API:

```
class MyClass {
    public void function(int i) {
        System.out.println(&quot;Hello, world!&quot;);
    }

    public static void main(final String... args) throws Throwable {
        final MethodHandle methodHandle = MethodHandles.publicLookup()
                 .findVirtual(MyClass.class, &quot;function&quot;, MethodType.methodType(void.class, int.class));

        final MyClass obj = new MyClass();
        methodHandle.invokeExact(obj, 42);
    }
}
```

A method reference from a class is simply named `Class::method`. That&#39;s it...

But you have to find a compatible type definition. Using `java.util.function` package, you can use `Consumer`s or `Function`s interfaces. Note that your function type must admit as a first parameter, the object on which the function should apply. (This differs from `instance_of_class::method` where the instance is embedded in the expression). 

You may also define your own lambda function signature (an interface with a single method).

Then, you can type:

```
import java.util.function.Consumer;

public class A {
	int a;
    void print_a() {
		System.out.println(a);
	}

	public static void main(String[] argv)
	{
		A aa = new A();
		aa.a = 42;
		Consumer&lt;A&gt; method = A::print_a;
		method.accept(aa);
	}
} 
```

Note that calling the reference uses the method of the lambda expression (`accept` with `Consumer`s, `apply` with `Function`s, and what ever you have used in a custom lambda interface).

