&gt; these logging frameworks define an interface library

Yes. Slf4j is the interface. The others are 2 implementations, but there are others like `java.util.logging` (JUL). 

You also need a [binding library](https://slf4j.org/manual.html#swapping) for a specific implentation. 

&gt; There is conflicting information available online. Some articles suggest log4j is used, some suggest slf4j

Both are accurate. log4j **1.x** (not 2, like you&#39;ve added) / reload4j is the implementation that Kafka uses, but uses it via the slf4j interfaces. 

&gt; Hence it is very hard to search for information, because the word &quot;log&quot; is used for multiple purposes

Writing to Console stdout/stderr, files, or Kafka is done with [&quot;appenders&quot;](https://logging.apache.org/log4j/2.x/log4j-core/apidocs/org/apache/logging/log4j/core/appender/mom/kafka/KafkaAppender.html) in log4j terms, not a &quot;logger&quot;. 

&gt; there is a failure, I would expect to be able to see some logging information printed to stdout

Only if you have a valid log _file_. Java does not include one for you. 

For example, you would need `src/main/resources/log4j2.xml` (create resources directory in your Maven project if not exists) to have the log4j2 library you&#39;ve added to log anything, anywhere.  

```xml
&lt;?xml version=&quot;1.0&quot; encoding=&quot;UTF-8&quot;?&gt;
&lt;Configuration status=&quot;WARN&quot;&gt;
    &lt;Appenders&gt;
        &lt;Console name=&quot;Console&quot; target=&quot;SYSTEM_OUT&quot;&gt;
            &lt;PatternLayout pattern=&quot;%d{HH:mm:ss.SSS} [%t] %-5level %logger{36} - %msg%n&quot;/&gt;
        &lt;/Console&gt;
    &lt;/Appenders&gt;
    &lt;Loggers&gt;
        &lt;Root level=&quot;DEBUG&quot;&gt; &lt;!-- everything as debug --&gt;
            &lt;AppenderRef ref=&quot;Console&quot;/&gt;
        &lt;/Root&gt;
        &lt;Logger name=&quot;org.apache.kafka&quot; level=&quot;INFO&quot;/&gt;  &lt;!-- except internal kafka packages --&gt;
    &lt;/Loggers&gt;
&lt;/Configuration&gt;
```

